      "title": "Module 1: Why \"just one\" is never just one",
      "text": "Every relapse in history began with a single cigarette that the person was certain would be the only one. The logic feels airtight in the moment — \"I've proved I can stop, so one won't undo anything.\" But it isn't one. One puff delivers a fresh dose of nicotine, which wakes the little monster that was almost dead. And it does something worse: it revives the big monster — the belief in your mind that the cigarette is available to you as an option. Once that door reopens, the second cigarette is far easier than the first was, and you're back in the chain you worked ten days to break.\n\nHere's the cruel twist that fools people. That first cigarette after stopping usually tastes awful. And the mind reads the awfulness as reassurance: \"See? I don't even enjoy it — clearly I'm not hooked, so I'm safe.\" Exactly backwards. The bad taste proves nothing except that your body has started to recover. Meanwhile the nicotine has already reached your brain and the chain has already restarted, quietly, beneath the conscious \"that was disgusting.\" The danger isn't in the taste. It's in the dose."
