      "title": "Module 2: The abstinence violation effect",
      "text": "Modern relapse-prevention psychology names a specific trap, and it's worth knowing by name: the abstinence violation effect. It works like this. You're committed to zero. Then one slip happens. And instead of treating it as a single, correctable event, the mind catastrophises: \"I've blown it. I'm a smoker again. I've failed, so I may as well finish the pack.\" The all-or-nothing thinking turns one cigarette into a full relapse — not because of the nicotine, but because of the interpretation.\n\nThis is why your stance toward \"just one\" has to be settled in advance, today, while you're calm. Two layers of protection. First and best: never take the puff — the rule is absolute precisely because it removes all the in-the-moment negotiating. Second, as a safety net: if a slip ever happened, you refuse the catastrophe. One cigarette is one mistake, not a verdict on you. You don't \"finish the pack.\" You stop, dust off, and return to free — which is exactly what Day 25 will rehearse in detail."
